,"1222–1260":"1222–1260","1182–Female":"1182–Zesnulá","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1190":"1190","about 1250":"okolo 1250","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","1182":"1182","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","about 1239":"okolo 1239","1224":"1224","1222":"1222","about 1220":"okolo 1220","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, Anglie","Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, Anglie","Ardleigh, Essex, England":"Ardleigh, Essex, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1220–about 1250":"omkring 1220–omkring 1250","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1222–1260":"1222–1260","1182–Female":"1182–Afdød","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1190":"1190","about 1250":"omkring 1250","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","1182":"1182","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","about 1239":"omkring 1239","1224":"1224","1222":"1222","about 1220":"omkring 1220","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Ardleigh, Essex, England":"Ardleigh, Essex, England"},"nl":{"about 1220–about 1250":"circa 1220–circa 1250","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1222–1260":"1222–1260","1182–Female":"1182–Overleden","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1190":"1190","about 1250":"circa 1250","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","1182":"1182","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","about 1239":"circa 1239","1224":"1224","1222":"1222","about 1220":"circa 1220","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Ardleigh, Essex, England":"Ardleigh, Essex, England"},"en":{"about 1220–about 1250":"about 1220–about 1250","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1222–1260":"1222–1260","1182–Female":"1182–Deceased","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1190":"1190","about 1250":"about 1250","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","1182":"1182","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","about 1239":"about 1239","1224":"1224","1222":"1222","about 1220":"about 1220","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Ardleigh, Essex, England":"Ardleigh, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>ston(e)</i> ‘stone, rock’ (Old English <i>stān</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on stony ground, by a notable outcrop of rock, or by a stone boundary-marker or monument, or habitational, from a place called Stone, such as those in Buckinghamshire, Devon, Gloucestershire, Hampshire, Kent, Somerset, Staffordshire, and Worcestershire.","Irish (Kilkenny): adopted for Irish <b>Ó Clochartaigh</b> (see   Clougherty  ) and/or <b>Ó Clochasaigh</b> (see   Clohessy  ), and possibly several other names containing or thought to contain the element <i>cloch</i> ‘stone’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of various surnames in other languages, meaning ‘stone’, including Jewish   Stein  , Norwegian <b>Steine</b>, French   Lapierre  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stoner","meanings":["English (Sussex): topographic name from Middle English <i>ston(e)</i> ‘stone’ + <i>-er</i>, used for someone who lived by a prominent rock or stone, or perhaps who came from a place called Stone, although this formation is more rare. See   Stone   and compare   Stoneman  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Steiner  ."]},{"name":"Stones","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Stone   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. A number of the places called Stone are sometimes recorded with plural spellings in the medieval period, including Stone (Staffordshire), recorded as <i>Stanes</i> in 1187."]},{"name":"Stenner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt.","German: occupational name for a stonemason or stonecutter, or a topographic name for someone who lived on stony ground, from a derivative of Middle High German <i>stein</i> ‘stone’, ‘stony place’. Compare   Stone   and   Stein  .","English: variant of   Stayner  ."]},{"name":"Clougherty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aileen.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Clochartaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Clochartach</i>’, a personal name, probably formed with <i>cloch</i> ‘stone’,   Stone   being an alternative Anglicized form of the surname."]},{"name":"Roach","meanings":["English:","of Norman origin, from Old French and Middle English <i>roche</i> ‘rock, cliff, promontory’, sometimes a translation of   Stone  . The surname may have been topographic, denoting someone who lived on or by a prominent rock or rocky place, or a habitational name for someone who lived or came from a place so named, such as one of those called Roque or Roche(s) in Normandy and neighboring regions, or Roche in Cornwall, Roach Farm in Clyst Hydon (Devon), or Roch in Pembrokeshire (see   Roch  ).","in Lancashire perhaps referring to the River Roch, which runs through Rochdale; the river name is probably a back-formation from <i>Recedham</i>, an early name for Rochdale recorded in 1086, derived from Old English <i>reced</i> ‘building, house, hall’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’. Alternatively, the Lancashire name could be a shortened form of the now rare or extinct surname <b>Rochdale</b> alias <b>Rachedale</b>, <i>Rachdall</i>, a habitational name from Rochdale (Lancashire). From the 18th century onward the name is difficult to distinguish from   Roch  , borne by Irish migrants to South Lancashire, especially Liverpool."]},{"name":"Stoneman","meanings":["English: perhaps an occupational name for someone who was the servant (Middle English <i>man</i>) of a person surnamed   Stone  . Alternatively, the name may have been an alias of   Stone  , used for someone who lived by a prominent stone or rock or at a minor place so named (Middle English <i>ston</i> + <i>man</i>).","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name for someone who worked with stone or who sold precious stones; a jeweler.","English: perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Ston(e)man</i> (Old English <i>Stān(e)mann</i>), a pet form of Old English personal names beginning with <i>Stān-</i> (from the word ‘stone’, ‘rock’) + the Old English hypocoristic suffix <i>-mann</i>."]}]},{"name":"Phillip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Philip  , in part a reflection of the surname, which is usually spelled <i>Phillips</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Earl Phillip Stone was born about 1220, in Ardleigh, Essex, England, his father, Sir Andrew Stone, was 31 and his mother, Stone, was 26. He married Matilda Desing about 1239, in Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1250, in his hometown, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1220–about 1250":"umbes 1220–umbes 1250","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1222–1260":"1222–1260","1182–Female":"1182–Surnud","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1190–1250":"1190–1250","119